Here you're close to being correct. The Workplace Shell was all 32-bit, but
most of PM and all of the graphics engine were 16-bit. Notice that in Warp,
only a very small part of PM is 16-bit.

>       Hmmmm.... MS Windows 3.1's interface is the shits.... wonder why
>people buy it?

Hmmm... My cat takes his medicine even though he doesn't like it. Wonder why?

(answer: it's crammed down his throat)

>       It isn't meant for desktop users.  At least not for non-Power
>user desktop guys.  Also, NT 3.5 is VERY fast.  Ask anyone using it.  And
>the support for Win16 and DOS apps has improved greatly.

PC Week seemed to think that it was much faster than NT 3.1, but still not as
fast as OS/2 2.1 (hence probably not as fast as Warp either).

>       Also, all they really did with OS/2 3.0 was optimize it, re-do
>some code to 32 bit, and add ALOT of apps in the base product as a
>reason for people to buy it.  To be honest, I haven't even heard of that
>many OS/2 apps in one place before, as are being bundled with 3.0.

The Workplace Shell was redone in a number of ways (fix the programming API,
add some requested things to the user interface). Also, they added Win32s
support.

>       To take the best advantage of OS/2, you need to use the HPFS
>filesystem, which requires formatting your drive (and/or partitioning).
>Why can't they do like MS, and add in a program for automatically
>changing it to HPFS?

A lot of the reason that HPFS is how it is today is because of your buddies in
Redmond. They own the rights to the design of HPFS, and IBM can't do much with
it other than what they've done already. (IBM has a history of making bad
business deals - Microsoft is just one of many).

>       And as some people have pointed out, it is apparently possible to
>fix the singe message queue in OS/2 without breaking all existing apps.
>So why doesn't IBM do this??

It's a very tricky bit of work. I wouldn't want to have to do it. Certainly
not something that can just be hacked up in a couple of weeks. (OS/2 still
takes extra care to make sure that moldy old 1.x apps like Microsoft Word
run on the latest versions of OS/2, you know. Unlike a certain other
company, IBM does not abandon its customers when it makes an updated release).

Warp was also originally just going to be a performance enhancement to 2.1 -
then it was decided to split off some of the new function scheduled for the
post-Warp release and put it into Warp; but not too much as to delay its
release into 1995.

